This paper is about improving the effectiveness of web search engines through query reformulation using an end-to-end encoder-decoder model. The paper uses convolutional neural networks and attention-based recurrent neural networks, which are commonly used in natural language processing and machine learning, suggesting that it may belong to the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category. The paper also focuses on information retrieval and improving retrieval performance, indicating that it may also belong to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses unsupervised learning, which is a common technique in machine learning and artificial intelligence, suggesting that it may belong to the cs.LG (Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-categories. Finally, the paper uses neural networks, which are a type of computational model that is commonly used in the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category.
